According to the LMOP documentation, the 'Waste in Place Year' field should correspond to that year's waste.¶

  • I checked their website for 2021 data, and it appears there is some newer data available for 2021.
  • This is something I'd ask for further clarification on, but I'm fairly confident that WIP is cumulative for all WIP years up to the current year based on quick research from this source: westcoastclimateforum.com/content/landfill-wip-and-mc-waste-place-methodology-landfilled-waste.

I visualized the data in QGIS to inspect the cause for the discrepancy in unique GHGRP ID's.¶

  • I also checked the possibility of there being missing ID's in the LMOP dataset by using the hub distance tool in QGIS on the records w/no ID. This tool gives the nearest point in another dataset with distance, I quickly checked the closest points in both datasets to check for similar addresses or facility names.

  • There weren't any close matches so I made the decision not to assume these should be cleaned/matched further.

ii. Compute a column for methane emissions data, assuming that 50% of the GHG QUANTITY (METRIC TONS CO2e) provided in the GHGRP dataset is from methane.¶

In [13]:
# Assuming half the emissions from 'GHG QUANTITY (METRIC TONS CO2e)' field is from methane
# convert the column to float and multiply by .5
methane = merged_df[ 'GHG QUANTITY (METRIC TONS CO2e)'].astype(float) * .5

# convert metric tons to kg
merged_df['methane_kg'] = methane * 1000

iii. Calculate methane intensity in kg CH4/ton of waste in place.¶

In [15]:
merged_df['methane_intensity'] = merged_df['methane_kg'] / wip.astype(float)

The top methane-producing county is LA county.¶

  • This makes sense because it is the most populous county in CA, and therefore more landfill waste is likely to be produced by its residents.
  • However, some counties in this analysis show no production of methane from landfills, which seems unlikely. There is a lack of GHGRP matching records in these counties.
In [25]:
import matplotlib.cm as cm
from matplotlib.colors import Normalize

LA_points = merged_counties.loc[merged_counties.NAME == 'Los Angeles']
LA_points['Waste in Place (tons)'] = pd.to_numeric(LA_points['Waste in Place (tons)'].str.replace(',',''),errors='coerce')
LA_points = LA_points.sort_values('Waste in Place (tons)', ascending=False)

# Shorten for readability
LA_points['Landfill Name'] = LA_points['Landfill Name'].str.split().str[:2].str.join(' ')

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))

# 3 bins to more easily distinguish methane intensity per each facility
LA_points['quantile'] = pd.qcut(LA_points['methane_intensity'], q=3, labels=False)
cmap = cm.get_cmap('cividis',3)
plt.bar(LA_points['Landfill Name'], LA_points['Waste in Place (tons)']/ 1e6, color=cmap(LA_points['quantile'] / 2),align="center")

plt.title('Methane Intensity per Landfill in LA County',size = 24)
plt.ylabel('Waste in Place (million tons)',size = 22)
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter('{:,.0f}'.format)

plt.xticks(rotation=75, size=16)
plt.yticks(size=16)

sm = cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap)
sm.set_array(LA_points['methane_intensity'])
cbar = plt.colorbar(sm)
cbar.set_label('Methane Intensity, kg/CH4 per metric ton', size=22)

plt.show()

This figure juxtaposes the emission intensity with the waste created by each landfill in the highest methane-producing county of Los Angeles. Interestingly, there doesn't seem to be a clear pattern with landfill size and the intensity of emissions. from matplotlib.cm import ScalarMappable

counties_methane['Waste in Place (tons)']= pd.to_numeric(counties_methane['Waste in Place (tons)'].str.replace(',','').fillna(np.nan), errors='coerce')
ca_counties_sum_methane = counties_methane.groupby('NAME').sum().reset_index()
county_geom=counties_methane[['NAME', 'geometry']].drop_duplicates(subset='NAME')
ca_counties_sum_methane = ca_counties_sum_methane.merge(county_geom, on='NAME').replace(0,np.nan)

ax = ca_counties_sum_methane.plot(
    column='Waste in Place (tons)',
    figsize=(18, 15),
    cmap='viridis', 
    edgecolor='black', 
    missing_kwds={
        "color": "lightgrey",
        "edgecolor": "white",
        "hatch": "///",
        "label": "No Data",
    })

ax.set_axis_off()
plt.title('Waste in Place by County, California', size=20)
normalize = Normalize(vmin=counties_methane['Waste in Place (tons)'].min(),
                 vmax=counties_methane['Waste in Place (tons)'].max())
sm = ScalarMappable(cmap='viridis', norm=normalize)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = plt.colorbar(sm, label='Waste in Place (hundred million tons)', ax=ax, 
                    fraction=0.05, pad=0.04, orientation='horizontal')
cbar.ax.tick_params(labelsize=16)
cbar.ax.set_xlabel('Waste in Place (hundred million tons)', fontsize=16)

plt.show()

This figure shows the total waste in place aggregated by county. Los Angeles is clearly leading in the amount of waste it produces, but it would be interesting to normalize this for population, number of landfills, or another assessment of landfill management practices by county.¶
